value.value: any structural anomaly of the outermost layer of the cerebral cortex that contains the parallel fibers of the granule cells, interneurons such as stellate and basket cells, and the dendrites of the underlying Purkinje cells

reduced width of the outermost layer of the cerebral cortex that contains the parallel fibers of the granule cells, interneurons such as stellate and basket cells, and the dendrites of the underlying Purkinje cells

any structural anomaly associated with the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

overdevelopment or increased size, usually due an increased number of cells associated with the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes
any structural anomaly of the inferior and superior colliculus
smaller inferior and superior colliculus
positional abnormality of the inferior and superior colliculus
any structural anomaly of the paired superior eminence of the mesencephalic tectum that is involved in auditory processing
enlargement of the paired superior eminence of the mesencephalic tectum

label.value: abnormal trigeminal V mesencephalic nucleus morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the group of sensory neurons residing in a long, narrow plate in the midbrain; axons pass with the trigeminal nerve
reduced size of the group of sensory neurons residing in a long, narrow plate in the midbrain; axons pass with the trigeminal nerve
missing group of sensory neurons residing in a long, narrow plate in the midbrain; axons pass with the trigeminal nerve
any structural anomaly of the group of motor neurons residing in the pons that innervate the muscles of facial expression
reduced size of the group of motor neurons residing in the pons that innervate the muscles of facial expression
any structural anomaly of the group of motor neurons innervating the muscles of mastication
reduced size of the group of motor neurons innervating the muscles of mastication
aberrant or incomplete differentiation of the brain
neurocranial defects resulting in exposure or extrusion of the brain
hydrocephaly due to a block in cerebrospinal fluid flow in the ventricular system
incomplete closure of the skull, usually congenital

any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons; oligodendrocytes in the brain and spinal cord and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system wrap axons with compact layers of their plasma membrane
a partial absence or patchy, incomplete area of a myelin sheath over all or part of an axon or fiber tract due to degeneration or destruction of the myelin sheath

definition.value: Demyelination is a term used to describe the destruction of the myelin sheath that surrounds axonal fibres. This is caused by diseases that damage the myelin sheath or the cells that form it.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the single row of specialized glial cells that occupies the dorsal midline of the developing neural tube along the entire anterior-posterior axis; the roof plate serves as a critical embryonic signaling center for the organization of dorsal neuronal cell types, and acts as a barrier preventing axons and cells migrating across the dorsal midline

absence of the single row of specialized glial cells that occupies the dorsal midline of the developing neural tube along the entire anterior-posterior axis; the roof plate serves as a critical embryonic signaling center for the organization of dorsal neuronal cell types, and acts as a barrier preventing axons and cells migrating across the dorsal midline

any structural anomaly of the specialized glial structure (non-neuronal cells) situated at the ventral midline of the embryonic neural tube; this structure spans the anteroposterior axis from the midbrain to the tail regions, separating the left and right basal plates of the developing neural tube, and serves as an organizer to ventralize tissues in the embryo as well as to guide neuronal positioning and differentiation along the dorsoventral axis of the neural tube

absence of the specialized glial structure (non-neuronal cells) situated at the ventral midline of the embryonic neural tube; this structure spans the anteroposterior axis from the midbrain to the tail regions, separating the left and right basal plates of the developing neural tube, and serves as an organizer to ventralize tissues in the embryo as well as to guide neuronal positioning and differentiation along the dorsoventral axis of the neural tube

reduced size of the specialized glial structure (non-neuronal cells) situated at the ventral midline of the embryonic neural tube; this structure spans the anteroposterior axis from the midbrain to the tail regions, separating the left and right basal plates of the developing neural tube, and serves as an organizer to ventralize tissues in the embryo as well as to guide neuronal positioning and differentiation along the dorsoventral axis of the neural tube
arrest of the fusion of the cephalic neural folds

definition.value: Head fold is properly used to describe the rostrally located, crescent shaped fold of the embryonic disc around the future foregut. However, it is often (and incorrectly) used as a synonym for the ventrally located cephalic neural folds. Take care to select the correct term.

value.value: failure of completion of the last step in the formation of the neural tube, where the paired neural folds are brought together and fuse at the dorsal midline
undulations in the embryonic neural tube
missing axial fibrocellular cord in embryos around which develops the vertebral primordia

any structural anomaly of any of the transiently divided segments of the developing neural tube of vertebrate embryos found within the hindbrain region in the area that will eventually become the rhombencephalon; the rhombomeres appear as a series of slightly constricted swellings in the neural tube, caudal to the cephalic flexure

anomaly in the progression of the enlarged anteriolateral part of the brain; consists of the paired cerebral hemispheres and olfactory bulbs, the basal ganglia and the connecting structures, and is considered to be the seat of conscious mental processes; it develops from the anterior-most embryological division of the brain that develops from the prosencephalon
malformation of the stereotypic invaginations forming the paired diverticula of the telencephalon
reduced size of the paired diverticula of the embryonic telencephalon, from which the forebrain develops
any structural anomaly of cells that innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of motor impulses
retrogressive impairment of function or destruction of the cells that innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of motor impulses
fewer than normal numbers of cells that innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of motor impulses
any changes in the placement, morphology or number of motor nerve fibers to an effector motor tissue, or failure of refinement of neuronal connections during development
seizures characterized by uncontrolled motor activity
seizures without uncontrolled motor activity, but with impairment of consciousness

label.value: abnormal seizure response to pharmacological agent

value.value: anomaly in the seizure activity response that is brought about by treatment with pharmacological agents
occasional seizures occurring at irregular intervals

any structural anomaly of non-neuronal cells of the central nervous system that form the myelin insulation of nervous pathways, guide neuronal migration during development, and exchange metabolites with neurons
any structural anomaly of the neuroglia of the central nervous system that form the insulating myelin sheath of axons in the CNS
fewer cells that differentiate into a type of glial cell in the central nervous system
any structural anomaly of the cylindrical tissue of the vertebral canal that extends from the medulla oblongata to the conus medullaris
smaller appearance of the spinal cord
a retrogressive impairment of function or destruction of the ganglia and peripheral nerves that lie outside the brain and spinal cord
any structural anomaly of the neural tissue involved in the transmission of sensory signals
